 its own ",[21,226,23],{}," keyword. The second idea, once you've got it down, basically lets you figure out where most ",[21,229,23],{}," references point. The last one is strict mode.",[17,232,233,234,236],{},"The course also lists the common ways ",[21,235,23],{}," gets invoked:",[17,238,239],{},[97,240],{"alt":241,"src":242},"common ways this is invoked","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-12-27%2022.53.28.png",[17,244,245,246,248],{},"So what's ",[21,247,23],{}," actually good for?",[17,250,251,252,254],{},"Basically, where ",[21,253,23],{}," points has nothing much to do with how you define the function. That means you can ignore how a function is defined and still use it to reach into a specific object's properties:",[17,256,257],{},[97,258],{"alt":259,"src":260},"what this is useful for","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-12-27%2023.05.34.png",[17,262,263,264,266],{},"And using ",[21,265,23],{}," inside an object's methods is super common:",[17,268,269],{},[97,270],{"alt":271,"src":272},"this in object method calls","https:\u002F\u002Fimages.israynotarray.com\u002FblogImg\u002FJavaScript\u002FJavaScript%20%E6%A0%B8%E5%BF%83%E8%A7%80%E5%BF%B5\u002F%E6%88%AA%E5%9C%96%202020-12-27%2023.07.25.png",[17,274,275],{},"So here's an example:",[39,277,279],{"className":41,"code":278,"language":43,"meta":44,"style":44},"var data = {\n  name: 'Ray',\n  callName() {\n    console.log(this.name);\n  },\n}\n\ndata.callName();\n",[21,280,281,293,304,312,326,331,335,339],{"__ignoreMap":44},[48,282,283,285,288,290],{"class":50,"line":51},[48,284,138],{"class":54},[48,286,287],{"class":62}," data ",[48,289,144],{"class":54},[48,291,292],{"class":62}," {\n",[48,294,295,298,301],{"class":50,"line":66},[48,296,297],{"class":62},"  name: ",